ce:section.ce:para:
To verify the attachment of CDs-oligo on the surface of AuNPs-oligo in the quenching process, we characterized Mode I and Mode II nanoprobes by TEM. Fig. 2
                        a and b clearly illustrates that a great deal of CDs-oligo was adsorbed on the surface of AuNPs-oligo. After the formation of AuNPs and CDs hybrid nanostructures, the particle size of Mode I and Mode II nanoprobes was increased to 20.18 ± 0.29 nm and 19.33 ± 1.66 nm, respectively. DLS results of Mode I and Mode II nanoprobes was increased to 144.72 ± 7.16 nm and 136.50 ± 2.09 nm, respectively (Fig. S4d and 4g). Further characterization of the nanostructures was to preformed to reveal whether the photoluminescence of CDs was quenched by AuNPs. If the CDs and AuNPs are close enough, it allows enough energy transfer from CDs to Au NPs. The energy transfer was confirmed by measuring the CDs donor lifetime using time-correlated single photon counting (TCSPC) (Fig. S7). The photoluminescence lifetime of the CDs was fitted to a biexponential decay in aqueous solution (Yaghini et al., 2014). A three-component lifetime of CDs and comparable fractional amplitudes were measured (Table 1
                        ). Average fluorescence lifetime of CDs is 3.85 ns. Additionally, the photoluminescence lifetime of the CDs was significantly reduced upon interaction with AuNPs (Fig. S7). For the AuNPs and CDs hybrid nanostructures, average fluorescence lifetimes of Mode I and Mode II nanoprobes are 2.76 ns and 1.80 ns. Such a decrease of lifetime in presence of the AuNPs is direct evidence of the fluorescence resonance energy transfer (Ajayaghosh et al., 2007).
